"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582041","Department of Health","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Local Authority Social Services and National Health Service Complaints (England) Regulations 2009 provide the legislative framework within which NHS complaints must be handled.</p><p> </p><p>There is no set timescale, though the body receiving the complaint must have arrangements in place to ensure it is dealt with efficiently, and the complainant receives a timely response.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-09-20T14:30:24.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582041/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582041/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-12","Patients: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the time period is within which NHS England has to respond to patients' complaints.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","45880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582042","Department of Health","false","2016-09-20","<p>This is a matter for Mid Yorkshire NHS Trust, which operates Pinderfields Hospital. Staffing levels are the responsibility of trust boards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-09-20T14:29:15.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582042/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582042/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-12","Pinderfields Hospital: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the adequacy of the numbers of staff at Pinderfields Hospital; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","45881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582043","Department of Health","false","2016-09-20","<p>These are matters for the local National Health Service. It is the responsibility of the Mid Yorkshire NHS Trust Board, its commissioners and regulators, and of the clinicians who work at the Trust, to ensure that the expected standards of care quality are being met.</p><p> </p><p>Patients at Mid Yorkshire NHS Trust deserve the highest quality care and there is no excuse for services to fall short of the standards. The Trust must take the necessary steps to improve its safety and leadership with the support of NHS Improvement.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-09-20T14:29:11.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582043/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582043/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-12","Pinderfields Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the Care Quality Commission report of December 2015, on Pinderfields Hospital; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","45897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582044","Department of Health","false","2016-09-15","<p>My noble Friend the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State (Lord Prior) met with representatives of the Prescription Charges Coalition on 25 May 2016.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-15T12:35:49.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582044/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582044/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-12","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has had any meetings with representatives of the Prescription Charges Coalition.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","45927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582045","Home Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) is able to bar individuals who pose a risk from working in certain roles with children, regardless of whether they have committed an offence. In addition, individuals working with children are eligible for Enhanced DBS certificates which, alongside criminal records information, disclose any non-conviction information that a chief officer believes to be relevant, for example Sexual Risk Orders.</p><p>The Government introduced Sexual Risk Orders (SRO) to protect the public from those who pose a risk of sexual harm but have not been convicted. The key elements of a SRO are that it may be made by the magistrates’ court on application by the police or National Crime Agency where an individual has done an act of a sexual nature and, as a result, is considered to pose a risk of harm to the public in the UK.</p><p>An SRO can be applied to any individual who poses a risk of sexual harm in the UK or abroad, even if they have never been convicted. An SRO may prohibit the person from doing anything described in it and any prohibition must be necessary for protecting the public in the UK from sexual harm. The Home Secretary has issued statutory guidance in relation to the orders to the police and the National Crime Agency.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-09-15T16:30:47.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582045/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582045/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Children: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what public protection orders or other legal instruments are available to prevent adults without violent or sexual convictions working with children in non-governed extracurricular sports or activities.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","45914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582046","Home Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>The family reunion policy allows those granted refugee status or humanitarian protection in the UK to sponsor their pre-flight family members, i.e. spouse or partner and children under the age of 18, who formed part of the family unit before the sponsor fled their country, to reunite with them in the UK.</p><p>Information on how many men, women and children have entered the UK under refugee family reunion provisions in the Immigration Rules is not captured in our published data and would require a manual review. This information cannot therefore be provided without exceeding proportionate costs.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-15T16:15:57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582046/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582046/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) men, (b) women and (c) children have entered the UK under the refugee family reunion rules in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","45935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582047","Home Office","false","2016-09-21","<p>Khat was controlled as a Class C drug under the Misuse of Drugs Act 1971 in 2014.</p><p>The 2015/16 Crime Survey England and Wales found that 0.06% of adults aged 16 to 59 in the general population had used khat in the last year, equivalent to around 20,000 people. This is similar to 2014/15 (0.05%) but a statistically significant fall compared with 0.2% in the previous two survey years when khat was measured (2010/11 and 2011/12).</p><p>We will continue to monitor the situation in relation to khat as appropriate, including through recommendations from the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs. Our approach to drugs remains clear: we must prevent drug use in our communities and help dependent individuals to recover, while ensuring our drugs laws are enforced.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-21T15:56:36.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582047/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582047/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Khat","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the effect of the ban on khat.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","45860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582048","Department of Health","false","2016-09-16","<p>NHS England advise that disclosure of pregnancy of women in held in immigration removal centres (IRCs) in England is at the behest of the individual concerned. The health assessment carried out at reception screening would ask if pregnancy was a possibility and a subsequent pregnancy test would confirm this, provided that consent was given.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office is currently consulting on mandatory new guidelines for its operational staff, “Care and Management of Pregnant women in Detention”. This will apply to staff operating in IRCs and other parts of the detention estate in England and is expected to be published this year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-09-16T14:40:56.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582048/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582048/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-12","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government takes to establish whether a woman is pregnant while in detention at an immigration removal centre.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","45862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582049","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>The average time taken to respond to electronic (e-mail or online) enquiries is unavailable in the format requested prior to July 2016.</p><p>From July 2016, the Security Industry Authority began using a new IT system, which has enabled it to produce a range of metrics. The average time taken to respond to electronic enquiries in July and August was 7 days against their service standard of 10 days.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-16T13:33:53.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582049/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582049/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Security Industry Authority: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average length of time taken was to respond to email enquiries by the Security Industry Authority in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","45918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582050","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Security Industry Authority (SIA) have an annual performance target to process 80% of applications (including renewals) within 25 working days. The SIA met this annual target in the 2015/16 financial year. Performance for 2016/17 to date is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Apr</p></td><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>Aug</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage processed in 25 working days</p></td><td><p>86%</p></td><td><p>81%</p></td><td><p>80%</p></td><td><p>46%</p></td><td><p>72%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-16T13:34:10.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582050/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582050/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Security Industry Authority: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Security Industry Authority has met its performance target of 80 per cent of applications being processed within 25 days in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","45919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582051","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>The average time taken to process 80% of applications (including renewals) within 25 working days is unavailable in the format requested.</p><p>The Security Industry Authority's (SIA’s) new IT system (introduced in July 2016) enables more detailed performance analysis. The system shows that the average number of days for processing applications (including renewals) was 38 days in July and 30 days in August.</p><p>Once fully embedded, the SIA expect that the processing time for applications will be quicker than under the old system.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-16T13:33:27.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582051/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582051/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Security Industry Authority: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken was to process applications and renewals by the Security Industry Authority in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","45916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582052","Home Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>Applicants for Security Industry Authority licences who have been unable to work while waiting for their licence to be renewed, and who request reimbursement for loss of earnings, can contact the Security Industry Authority to provide evidence of the loss suffered. Payment of compensation will then be considered, based on the evidence provided and a review of all the circumstances of the application.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-16T13:37:45.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582052/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582052/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582052/answer/previousversion/11770","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Security Guards: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what provisions the Security Industry Authority (SIA) has in place to compensate individuals who have lost their job as a result of delays of problems in SIA licence applications or renewals.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","45917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582053","Home Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>The overarching purpose of the COMPASS Inspection Regime is to ensure that the accommodation provided is safe, habitable, fit for purpose; that the overall service described in the COMPASS contracts is being delivered and to ensure that Service Users feel safe, secure and know how to raise concerns should they occur.</p><p>Following on from the audit into asylum seeker accommodation in Middlesbrough, UKVI have trialled various methods of gathering, recording and responding to service users’ feedback relating to service delivery as part of improving their inspection regime.</p><p>Following analysis from the trials conducted UKVI intends to agree a formal process which is to be rolled out across all provider Regions.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-15T14:40:14.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582053/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582053/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has conducted surveys with asylum seekers accommodated under her Compass contracts on what they felt about their (a) housing and (b) treatment by staff.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","45986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582054","Home Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>We continue to work closely with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to identify appropriate cases that they deem in need of resettlement for the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme, the Gateway Protection Programme and the Mandate Refugee Scheme.</p><p>Statistics on arrivals under each of these schemes are published in the regular quarterly Immigration Statistics in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. The next set of statistics will be in the quarterly release on 1 December 2016 and will cover the period July – September 2016. We do not publish a breakdown of these statistics by religion or ethnicity.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-15T16:16:09.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582054/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582054/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Refugees: Yazidis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Yazidi refugees have been supported into the UK from (a) Syria and (b) Iraq through the (i) Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme, (ii) Gateway Protection Programme and (iii) Mandate Refugee Scheme.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582055","Home Office","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Government has engaged with a number of international partners on the implementation of the Temporary Exclusion Order power. The Government made clear throughout the passage of the Counter-Terrorism and Security Bill that the operation of the TEO power would depend on the circumstances of each case and on the country from which an individual is seeking to travel to the UK. We will not comment on individual cases.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-09-20T13:55:01.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582055/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582055/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Temporary Exclusion Orders: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has (a) made any arrangements and (b) had any discussions with the governments of each country in the Middle East on the application of Temporary Exclusion Orders in those countries.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","45965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582056","Home Office","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Court Rules for Temporary Exclusion Orders provide for the disclosure of open material, the use of private hearings, and the withholding of closed material (the disclosure of which would be contrary to the public interest). The Home Office cannot determine which information is closed and must submit an application to the court for permission not to disclose certain information. Under the closed material procedure, the TEO subject and his legal representatives would attend ‘open’ court proceedings but would not be present at ‘closed’ proceedings. Special advocates appointed by the Attorney General would represent the interests of the excluded party in relation to closed evidence. The use of closed material proceedings is designed to ensure that the court has sight of sensitive material whilst protecting it from wider disclosure.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-09-20T13:51:56.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582056/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582056/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Temporary Exclusion Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the process is for considering whether to withhold sensitive material from courts to aid their consideration of (a) whether to impose Temporary Exclusion Orders (TEOs), (b) whether a TEO already imposed should be revoked and (c) whether the conditions imposed on those subject to TEOs are fair.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","46023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582057","Home Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>Since 2012 UKVI has discharged their statutory duty to provide destitute asylum seekers with accommodation and transportation via a suite of contracts known as COMPASS Contracts.</p><p>There are six COMPASS Contracts delivered by three providers: G4S deliver services in the North East, Yorkshire &amp; Humberside Region and the Midlands and East of England Region; Serco deliver services in the North West Region and Scotland and Northern Ireland. Clearsprings Ready Homes (formerly known as Clearel Ltd) deliver services in London and the South of England Region and Wales.</p><p>Whilst none of the COMPASS accommodation providers are registered social landlords, all are contractually required to provide safe, habitable, fit for purpose and correctly equipped accommodation to comply with the standards outlined within Housing legislation (regardless of whether the provider is registered as a social landlord).</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-15T14:39:45.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582057/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582057/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2016 to Question 42791, if she will publish the list her Department holds of the registered social landlords being used as at 30 August 2016 for the provision of compass accommodation to asylum seekers.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","46027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582058","Home Office","false","2016-09-22","<p>Decisions on uniform requirements for different roles within their force are for Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs).</p><p>The police remain operationally independent and it is for Chief Constables and PCCs locally to decide how to best equip their staff.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-22T16:00:14.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582058/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582058/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Police: Uniforms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect on the self-esteem of female police officers of having to wear a uniform.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","45996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582059","Home Office","false","2016-09-22","<p>Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) are best placed to decide the uniform requirements for different roles within their force.</p><p>The police remain operationally independent and it is for local leadership to ensure that officers can perform their duties effectively whilst taking officer safety, appropriate risk assessments and effective engagement with the public into consideration.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","46013","2016-09-22T15:39:28.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582059/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582059/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Police: Uniforms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is her policy to allow police officers to cover their faces for religious purposes.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","46012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582060","Home Office","false","2016-09-22","<p>Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) are best placed to decide the uniform requirements for different roles within their force.</p><p>The police remain operationally independent and it is for local leadership to ensure that officers can perform their duties effectively whilst taking officer safety, appropriate risk assessments and effective engagement with the public into consideration.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","46012","2016-09-22T15:39:28.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582060/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582060/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Police: Uniforms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has the ability to overrule chief constables on decisions about uniform policy.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","46013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582061","Home Office","false","2016-09-26","<p>Decisions about the policing priorities in Cumbria are a matter for the locally elected and accountable Police and Crime Commissioner. In Cumbria, police recorded crime fell by 5% between June 2010 and March 2016.</p><p>In 2016/17, direct resource funding to Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs), including precept (the element of police funding derived from council tax), has been protected to at least flat cash levels. This means that no PCC who chose to maximise precept is facing a reduction in cash funding in 2016/17 compared to 2015/16 and the majority are seeing marginal cash increases in their spending power.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-26T16:35:11.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582061/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582061/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-12","Cumbria Constabulary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will set out her plans for the future of Cumbria Police; and whether that police force's (a) budget and (b) number of police officers will be reduced in the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","46030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582062","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-15","<p>Since June 2014, the UK has committed £129.5 million in humanitarian assistance to the crisis in Iraq. This includes the UK’s contribution to the UN Iraq Humanitarian Pooled Fund. The Pooled Fund, and other DFID funded projects, have provided access to emergency life-saving health services, emergency vaccines for vulnerable children, and expansion of maternity and child health care – including to internally displaced people in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq. Our cash programming, focussed in the north of the country, helps the most vulnerable people in Iraq to buy medicines and access the medical treatment that they urgently need.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-15T16:52:15.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582062/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582062/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Kurds: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department provides for medical support for internally displaced people in Kurdistan.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582063","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-19","<p>The UK deplores incitement to violence on both sides of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict and takes the issue of incitement extremely seriously. When incidents of incitement to violence do occur, we do not hesitate to raise and condemn these with the Palestinian Authority. The UK raises the issue of incitement as part of the FCO-led UK-Palestinian strategic dialogue, most recently in February this year. HMG’s assessment is that the Palestinian Authority is not in breach of the Memorandum of Understanding. The UK continues to encourage the leaderships of both the PA and Israel to re-engage in the Trilateral Committee on Anti-Incitement.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-09-19T12:27:34.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582063/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582063/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has made a recent assessment of the level of adherence by the Palestinian National Authority to the principle of non-violence set out in the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and that authority; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","45929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582064","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-19","<p>The last formal assessment of the Palestinian Authority’s (PA) commitment to the Partnership Principles, including the PA’s commitment to respecting human rights, was carried out in May 2016. Our assessment is that the PA continues to deliver on the Partnership Principles, even under increasingly fragile and volatile conditions.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-09-19T12:28:33.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582064/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582064/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Palestinian Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when her Department last made a formal assessment of the Palestinian National Authority's adherence to its commitment to ensure that the human rights of all citizens are respected without exception as set out in the Memorandum of Understanding between her Department and that authority; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","45930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582065","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-15","<p>DFID will make an assessment of how we will work with the European Union Institutions as part of the exit negotiations and we look forward to working with all of our international partners in future to achieve the best results possible.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-15T16:44:01.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582065/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582065/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with officials in her Department on the potential effect of the outcome of the EU referendum on recipients of overseas development assistance currently given to (a) the European Development Fund, (b) the European Commission Humanitarian Aid and Civil Protection department and (c) the European Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","45921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582066","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-15","<p>The vast majority of DFID’s work is not done via the EU. We remain committed to spending 0.7% of our national income on development assistance, and to achieving the UN’s Global Goals and ending extreme poverty by 2030. We will continue to help countries in the developing world leave aid dependency behind to become our trading partners of the future.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-15T16:45:18.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582066/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582066/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of which policy areas in her Department will be affected by the UK vote to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","45922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582067","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-15","<p>We remain committed to spending 0.7% of our national income on development assistance, and to achieving the UN’s Global Goals and ending extreme poverty by 2030. Outside of the EU we will have better control over where we are spending our money. We will continue to uphold our manifesto commitments on UK international development.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-15T16:46:44.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582067/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582067/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has made to reallocate UK aid funding from cross-EU funds and programmes.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","45923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582068","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-15","<p>Table 1 below provides the estimated proportion of Official Development Assistance (ODA) to be spent by other government departments and cross-government funds based on the Spending Review 2015 settlement. Funding is dispersed across a wide range of departments and cross-government funds. Expected proportions are based on ODA budget allocations announced at Spending Review 2015 in order to meet the government’s commitment to spend 0.7 per cent of Gross National Income (GNI) on ODA in each calendar year. Adjustments will be made to the ODA budget to reflect the latest economic forecasts throughout the spending review period.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: Expected proportion of ODA to be spent by other government departments based on Spending Review 2015 settlement, 2016/17-2019/20</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>2019/20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-DFID departmental spend (incl cross-gov funds)</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td><td><p>21%</p></td><td><p>24%</p></td><td><p>26%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-15T16:49:22.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582068/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582068/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of overseas development assistance she estimates will be spent by departments other than her Department for each year until 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","45924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582069","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-15","<p>One member of DFID staff has taken up a Grade 6 role within the Department for Exiting the European Union on a loan basis. We expect that several DFID staff will be strong candidates for other roles in the new Department currently being advertised.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-09-15T16:50:05.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582069/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582069/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-12","Department for International Development: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many full-time equivalent officials in her Department have been seconded to the Department for Exiting the European Union; and what the grades are of those officials.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","45925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582070","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-15","<p>Court Reporting &amp; Transcription Project Costs are currently estimated at £687k.</p><p> </p><p>This relates to MOJ staff costs, the use of external advice in the preparation of contracts and conducting due diligence tests of bidders.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-15T16:51:52.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582070/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582070/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Law Reporting: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the cost to date has been of the current tender process for civil and crown court reporting and transcribing services.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","45913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582071","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-15","<p>Her Majesty’s Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) has issued an Invitation to Tender for the future provision of court transcription services. The successful bidders will provide transcription services under a four year framework agreement, the value of which is estimated at between £20m and £28m over the term of the agreement.</p><p> </p><p>We are not in a position to disclose the proposed budget in any greater detail than outlined above for court reporting and transcription services whilst the competition is still running as this may undermine the Authority’s commercial position.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-15T10:01:50.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582071/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582071/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Law Reporting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the proposed budget is for court reporting and transcribing services after the completion of the current tender process.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","45911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582072","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-15","<p>The table below shows the amount spent on court reporting and transcription services in civil and Crown courts in England &amp; Wales for each financial year from 2011 to 2015.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Civil &amp; Family</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Crown Courts</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-2011</strong></p></td><td><p>Not Available</p></td><td><p>Not Available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-2012</strong></p></td><td><p>£4,101,318.83</p></td><td><p>£4,101,339.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-2013</strong></p></td><td><p>£4,371,822.48</p></td><td><p>£1,953,877.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p>£4,458,233.95</p></td><td><p>£2,042,664.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td><td><p>£4,673,564.18</p></td><td><p>£2,447,053.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015-2016</strong></p></td><td><p>Not Yet Available</p></td><td><p>Not Yet Available</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Civil and Family figures refer to the value of court reporting &amp; transcription services received by all users of the services where the case was heard:</p><ul><li>in County Courts;</li><li>in High Court (including district registries); and</li><li>in the Court of Appeal (Criminal and Divisions)</li></ul><p> </p><p>The Crown Courts figures refer to the value of court reporting &amp; transcription services received by all users of the services where the case was heard in a Crown Court in England and Wales.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-15T16:52:43.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582072/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582072/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Law Reporting: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been spent on court reporting and transcribing services in (a) civil and (b) Crown courts in England and Wales in each financial year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","45912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582073","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-20","<p>All prison officers working in public sector prisons and young offender institutions are required to wear uniform as part of their conditions of service. Uniform is provided partly as a security measure to aid the immediate identification of staff. There has been no assessment of the self-esteem of either female or male officers in being required to wear uniform.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-20T11:26:20.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582073/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582073/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Prison Officers: Uniforms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the effect on the self-esteem of female prison officers of having to wear a uniform.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","45995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582074","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-20","<p>This information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-20T11:08:09.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582074/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582074/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Remand in Custody: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of (i) men and (ii) women were refused bail and remanded in custody when the alleged offence related to an incident involving domestic violence in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582075","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-30","<p>The Bail Act 1976 creates a presumption in favour of bail. The main reasons for refusing bail are that the defendant is accused of an imprisonable offence and the court is satisfied that there are substantial grounds for believing that the defendant, if released on bail, would abscond, commit further offences while on bail or interfere with witnesses or otherwise obstruct the course of justice. In deciding whether or not to grant bail, the court will consider a number of factors, including: the nature and seriousness of the crime; the character of the defendant; his past criminal record; associations and ties with the community; the defendant’s record in regard to his previous commitments to bail conditions; and the strength of evidence against the defendant.</p><p>The number and proportion of offenders remanded in custody before conviction for violence against the person, public order offences, harassment or sexual offences, by gender, at magistrates’ courts and the Crown Court in England and Wales in 2015, can be viewed in the attached table.</p><p>Court proceedings data for 2016 will be published in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-30T12:32:54.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582075/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582075/answer","Table for PQ 46055.xls","Table for PQ 46055.xls","Table for PQ 46055","Table for PQ 46055","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582075/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Remand in Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of (i) men and (ii) women were refused bail and remanded in custody before conviction when the allegation related to (A) an offence against the person, (B) a public order offence, (C) a harassment offence and (D) a sexual offence in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582076","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-20","Robust and reliable information on post-conviction remand status of offenders convicted at the Crown Court is not centrally held, and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-20T11:42:16.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582076/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582076/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders in each offence category were released on post-conviction bail by Crown Courts in each of the last three years; and (a) how many and (b) in what proportion of such cases the offender received a custodial sentence.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582077","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-30","<p>The number and proportion of offenders appearing at the Crown Court for offences of common assault and battery who were remanded in custody prior to their conviction, in England and Wales, 2010 to 2014, can be viewed in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>The table also includes data on remand status for offenders convicted of common assault and battery in the magistrates’ court between 2013 and 2014. Unfortunately data prior to 2013 could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Court proceedings data for 2016 are planned for publication in summer 2017.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="7"><p><strong>The number and proportion of offenders<sup>(1)</sup> appearing at the Crown Court for offences of common assault and battery who were remanded in custody<sup>(2) </sup>prior to their conviction, England and Wales, 2010 - 2014<sup>(3) (4) (5)</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012<sup>(6)</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Offenders remanded in custody prior to conviction for common assault and battery</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>515</p></td><td><p>534</p></td><td><p>391</p></td><td><p>450</p></td><td><p>562</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Proportion of offenders remanded in custody prior to conviction for common assault and battery<sup>(7)</sup></em></p></td><td><p><em> </em></p></td><td><p><em>24.1</em></p></td><td><p><em>27.8</em></p></td><td><p><em>26.9</em></p></td><td><p><em>33.1</em></p></td><td><p><em>40.8</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(1) Excludes persons where sex &quot;Not Stated&quot; and other offenders, i.e. companies, public bodies, etc.'</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(2) Includes those who were remanded in custody prior to conviction who may also have been granted bail on another occasion prior to conviction.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(3) The figures given in the table relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When an offender has been cautioned for or found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(4) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(5) Data will not necessarily match published remanded in custody data. This is because the published data are produced using a different methodology, whereby one principal remand status involving the greatest degree of court control is determined. A defendant would be counted as remanded in custody if at any period of the trial he or she was given custodial remand.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(6) The 'associated person exception to bail' provision came into force on 3rd December 2012 A defendant need not be granted bail if there are substantial grounds for believing that the defendant if released on bail (whether subject to conditions or not) would commit an offence on bail by engaging in conduct that would or would be likely to cause physical or mental injury or fear of the same to an associated person. ‘Associated person’ is defined in section 62 Family Law Act 1996’.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="7"><p>(7) As a proportion of all offenders convicted at the Crown Court for offences of common assault and battery.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-30T09:38:34.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582077/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582077/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Remand in Custody: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in (a) how many and (b) what proportion of cases involving common assault was someone remanded in custody prior to their conviction in the two years (i) prior to and (ii) following the introduction of the associated person exception to bail.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582078","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-29","<p>The number and proportion of male and female offenders remanded in custody before conviction for violence against the person offences, at magistrates’ courts and the Crown Court in England and Wales, between 2013 and 2015, can be viewed in the table.</p><p>Reliable information on post-conviction remand status for offenders convicted at Crown and magistrates’ courts is not centrally held and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Court proceedings data for 2016 will be published in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-29T19:46:06.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582078/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582078/answer","Table for PQ 46053.xlsx","Table for PQ 46053.xlsx","Table for PQ 46053","Table for PQ 46053","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582078/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Prisoners on Remand: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of (i) male and (ii) female offenders convicted of each offence in the violence against the person offence category were remanded in custody (A) pre-conviction and (B) post-conviction in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582079","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Offender Rehabilitation Act 2014, which introduced post sentence supervision for those serving short custodial sentences, applies to offences committed on or after 1 February 2015. Statistics on the number of offenders starting post sentence supervision and the number of offenders committed to custody for breach of post sentence supervision conditions is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/541247/probation-q1-2016.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/541247/probation-q1-2016.xlsx</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","46051 ; 46052","2016-09-20T11:33:24.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582079/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582079/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Supervision Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of offenders who breached a Supervision Default Order were (i) sent to prison and (ii) not sent to prison since the introduction of such Orders.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582080","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Offender Rehabilitation Act 2014, which introduced post sentence supervision for those serving short custodial sentences, applies to offences committed on or after 1 February 2015. Statistics on the number of offenders starting post sentence supervision and the number of offenders committed to custody for breach of post sentence supervision conditions is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/541247/probation-q1-2016.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/541247/probation-q1-2016.xlsx</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","46050 ; 46052","2016-09-20T11:33:24.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582080/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582080/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of offenders who have been taken to court for breaching their post sentence supervision were (i) fined, (ii) given a Supervision Default Order, (iii) committed to prison and (iv) had no action taken against them since the introduction of such supervision.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582081","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Offender Rehabilitation Act 2014, which introduced post sentence supervision for those serving short custodial sentences, applies to offences committed on or after 1 February 2015. Statistics on the number of offenders starting post sentence supervision and the number of offenders committed to custody for breach of post sentence supervision conditions is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/541247/probation-q1-2016.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/541247/probation-q1-2016.xlsx</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","46050 ; 46051","2016-09-20T11:33:24.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582081/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582081/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-12","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of offenders who breached their post sentence supervision have been taken to court since the introduction of such supervision.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","46052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582082","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-09-14","<p>My Department does not hold this information and to obtain it would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>My department has two executive non-departmental public bodies – the Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission and the Parades Commission for Northern Ireland; and one advisory non-departmental public body – the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland. As these bodies are independent of Government, the hon Member may wish to write to the Commissions directly on these matters – contact details are set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>ALB</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Status</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contact Details</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parades Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>Executive NDPB</p></td><td><p>info@paradescommission.org</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission</p></td><td><p>Executive NDPB</p></td><td><p>information@nihrc.org</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p>Advisory NDPB</p></td><td><p>contact@boundarycommission.org.uk</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-09-14T12:07:58.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582082/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582082/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-09-12","Northern Ireland Office: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many citizens of EU countries other than the UK work in (a) his Department and (b) agencies and other bodies for which his Department is responsible.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","45953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582083","Scotland Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. All staff that join, do so on assignment, loan or secondment, principally from the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government; who remain the employers. Details of staff nationality and ethnicity is retained by the parent department.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-09-15T08:59:19.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582083/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582083/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-09-12","Scotland Office: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many citizens of EU countries other than the UK work in (a) his Department and (b) agencies and other bodies for which his Department is responsible.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","45954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582084","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2016-09-14","<p>The Electoral Commission welcomed the publication of Sir Eric Pickles' review into electoral fraud and is now carefully considering the detail of its recommendations. The Commission has noted that the review supports a number of its own longstanding recommendations, including its call for voter ID, first put forward in 2014.</p><p>The Commission is an independent statutory body which reports and is accountable to the UK and Scottish Parliaments. It will publish a full response to Sir Eric’s review in due course and a copy will be placed in the House Library.</p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2016-09-14T11:41:25.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582084/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582084/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2016-09-12","Electoral Fraud Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, what response the Electoral Commission has made to paragraphs 214 to 226 of the Report entitled, Securing the ballot, Report of Sir Eric Pickles' review into electoral fraud, published in August 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","46022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582085","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Infrastructure and Projects Authority (IPA) provides expertise, practical help and independent assurance of major projects, working with all partners in infrastructure and major projects (government departments, project teams, HMT, Cabinet Office, and the private sector). The remit of the IPA does not include providing formal approval and as such departments do not submit business cases to the IPA for approval.</p><p> </p><p>The IPA publish an annual comprehensive forward-looking assessment of the current and planned investment in UK economic infrastructure across both the public and private sectors (The National Infrastructure Pipeline). This document contains financial information of the level of public and private infrastructure investment broken down by region currently in development and planned to 2021 and beyond. The Spring 2016 update can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-infrastructure-pipeline-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-infrastructure-pipeline-2016</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","46060","2016-09-16T13:47:19.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582085/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582085/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Transport: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many business cases for projects were submitted to his Department in the 2015-16 financial year in each region; and what the value was of (a) public and (b) private investment requested at stage two of each of those submissions in each such region.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","46021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582086","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Department for Transport does not make payments to Network Rail on a route by route basis.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-15T09:41:38.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582086/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582086/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what payments his Department has made or is projected to make to Network Rail in respect of the rail network used by Govia Thameslink Railway for each financial year of the franchise period.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","46063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582087","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>As was stated when the franchise was awarded to Govia Thameslink Railway, the Thameslink Southern and Great Northern franchise is let as a management contract, where ticket revenues are passed directly to the Government rather than retained by Govia. This means that this franchise does not have premium/ subsidy payments.</p><p> </p><p>In respect of part (a) Prior year figures are published by the ORR: <a href="http://orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/gb-rail-industry-financial-information" target="_blank">http://orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/gb-rail-industry-financial-information</a></p><p> </p><p>In relation to part (b), in February 2015 a Franchise Payment Profile was deposited in the Library of the house; this contained the following information with regard to Govia Thameslink Railway:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Franchises - current as at 25 Feb 2015 </strong></p><p><strong>Franchise Payment profile to 2023 (in NOMINAL £) </strong></p><p> </p><p>Caveats</p><p>All figures are based on current franchise agreements including the current estimates for Control Period 5 and fares policy adjustments. The figures do not include revenue support, revenue share, profit share, or adjustments for GDP.</p><p>All figures are subject to change in the future as a result of negotiated contractual changes and changes to inflation indices above or below that assumed.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2015/16 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017/18 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018/19 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019/20 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020/21 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2021/22 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>275,405,206</p></td><td><p>403,760,328</p></td><td><p>424,690,456</p></td><td><p>404,131,348</p></td><td><p>497,212,369</p></td><td><p>587,111,514</p></td><td><p>303,608,193</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures represent the net balance between payments made under the Management Contract and revenue received, and indicate a payment from the Train Operating Company to the department.</p><p> </p><p>The moneys paid to the Department by the Train Operator contribute to the overall budget for the provision of passenger rail services.</p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to continuing to invest in passenger rail and, for example, we are investing more than £1.6billion of taxpayers’ money in new, longer, and more spacious Thameslink trains. We have also recently announced a targeted £20m fund, to be spent by Network Rail under project board authority, to help get Southern rail services back running as they should.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-15T14:35:14.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582087/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582087/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Govia Thameslink Railway: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) has been and (b) is the projected balance between the fee paid to Govia Thameslink Railway for delivering the current franchise and the income from fares for each financial year of the franchise period.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","46064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582088","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Infrastructure and Projects Authority (IPA) provides expertise, practical help and independent assurance of major projects, working with all partners in infrastructure and major projects (government departments, project teams, HMT, Cabinet Office, and the private sector). The remit of the IPA does not include providing formal approval and as such departments do not submit business cases to the IPA for approval.</p><p> </p><p>The IPA publish an annual comprehensive forward-looking assessment of the current and planned investment in UK economic infrastructure across both the public and private sectors (The National Infrastructure Pipeline). This document contains financial information of the level of public and private infrastructure investment broken down by region currently in development and planned to 2021 and beyond. The Spring 2016 update can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-infrastructure-pipeline-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-infrastructure-pipeline-2016</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","46021","2016-09-16T13:47:19.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582088/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582088/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Transport: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many large-scale business cases submitted by his Department to the Infrastructure and Projects Authority were accepted in the 2015-16 financial year in each region; and what the value of (a) public and (b) private sector funding committed was for each of those projects in each such region.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","46060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582089","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>This Government knows the public is concerned about the price of petrol and diesel at Motorway Service Areas. Highways England is, on behalf of the Government, delivering an 18 month trial of four fuel comparison price signs on the M5 between Bristol and Exeter.</p><p> </p><p>The trial consists of four new electronic signs displaying real-time price information of petrol and diesel for the next three service areas along the route and commenced in Spring 2016. Monitoring and evaluation of the trial will determine the effectiveness of the new fuel comparison price signs in providing useful information to road users and in understanding the impact of improving fuel price transparency on driver behaviour and fuel prices at Motorway Service Areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-20T08:45:36.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582089/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582089/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Motorway Service Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will implement the proposal set out on page 326 of the OECD Policy Roundtable on Competition in Road Fuel to introduce road signs displaying the price of petrol and diesel at motorway service stations in order to improve transparency and consumer choice.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","45957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582090","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>Funding for the proposed Isham Bypass (also known as the A509 Wellingborough Development Link) was provisionally approved by the Government in 2014 as part of the Northamptonshire Growth Deal. This approval is subject to the scheme promoters, Northamptonshire County Council, obtaining any necessary statutory permissions and submitting to the Department a Final Business Case for approval.</p><p> </p><p>The Council expects to submit a Final Business Case in March 2017. Ministers will then make a final funding decision, as quickly as possible thereafter, on whether to support the scheme. The Council’s current programme is to start construction in September 2017 and to open the completed road in April 2019.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-15T14:22:49.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582090/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582090/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Bypasses: Wellingborough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce when construction of the Isham bypass in Wellingborough constituency will (a) commence and (b) be finished.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","45987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582091","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>The current number of grey speed cameras on our network is 27. The Highways England programme of work is currently on target to ensure all grey speed cameras on the network are yellow by October 2016</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-15T12:22:58.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582091/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582091/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Speed Limits: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 45389, and with reference to his Department's press release, End of the road for grey speed cameras, published on 14 November 2015, how many camera sites that are on the motorway network currently contain working grey speed cameras; and what recent assessment he has made of Highways England's progress in meeting the target of painting all working speed cameras yellow by October 2016.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582092","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>We are currently working with Network Rail to ensure that the majority of Access for All stations will have at least a design completed in this rail Control Period. This will ensure that stations that have construction deferred will be ready to start on site as early as possible once funding is available again in 2019/20. We expect to announce which stations will be affected shortly.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-15T10:41:43.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582092/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582092/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Railway Stations: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 45155, at which stations will planned Control Period 5 Access for all improvements be deferred into Control Period 6 in connection with his decision to accept the Hendy Review.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582093","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Department commissions a wide range of research to support its objectives. The general presumption is that research results used in the course of the Department’s business should be made available to broaden knowledge and better inform discussion. In a few circumstances (for instance, where the research relates to security matters or where the Department does not hold the necessary rights to publish) such information is not published; but such circumstances are exceptional. Information on publication of the outputs of this research is not collected centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-20T08:55:25.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582093/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582093/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Department for Transport: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which reports commissioned by his Department from external bodies between 1 January 2015 and 31 August 2016 have not yet been published; when each report was commissioned for research; what the nature of the research commissioned was; from which external body or individual person the research was commissioned; what the value was of each such piece of research commissioned; on what date each report was received by his Department; for what reasons the research has not yet been published; and when he plans to publish each report.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","45907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582094","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Government recognises how important improving access to public transport is for disabled people and is committed to making transport more inclusive.</p><p> </p><p>Since its launch in 2006, the £390m Access for All rail programme (which was further extended with £160m in 2014) has delivered accessible routes at over 150 stations. There are also 68 further projects at various stages of construction or development.</p><p> </p><p>We also recognise that positive interactions with bus drivers can make a big difference to disabled people’s experience of taking the bus. We are working with the bus industry and disabled people to design best practice guidance in delivering disability awareness training which, we hope, will help to give bus drivers the skills and knowledge to assist every disabled passenger.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Bus Services Bill will specifically allow enhanced partnership schemes to require all buses within a local area to provide audible and visual next stop information. Authorities using the new franchising powers will be able to place similar requirements on affected operators. The Government has also agreed to consider amendments on this issue which were tabled during the Bill’s committee stage in the House of Lords.</p><p> </p><p>The Government intends to publish an Accessibility Action Plan by the end of the year which will present its ambition for further progress on this important agenda.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-16T13:54:34.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582094/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582094/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Public Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve access to public transport for disabled people.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","45936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582095","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>Government is committed to giving disabled people the same access to transport services as other members of society. It also recognises the particularly significant role played by taxis and private hire vehicle (PHV) operators for many disabled people, in helping them to remain active and independent.</p><p> </p><p>It is for local authorities to specify a number of accessible vehicles to be within their licensed taxi and private hire vehicle fleet, and to take account of their public sector equality duties when doing so.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-20T14:07:42.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582095/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582095/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase the number of accessible taxis in the UK.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","45937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582096","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>Highways England is currently identifying and assessing options for the Trans Pennine Routes which includes the Mottram by-pass. A public consultation on the Preferred Route is currently planned to take place in early 2017. There will also be two public awareness events in October 2016 which will provide an opportunity for people in the local communities to meet the project team, receive an update on progress and provide feedback which can then be used in the development of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Planning permission for this scheme will require an application for a Development Consent Order and start of works is planned by March 2020 in line with the Highways England’s Delivery Plan 2015 – 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-16T14:20:30.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582096/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582096/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Tintwistle, Hollingworth and Mottram Bypass","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will provide an update on his Department's preparations for the Mottram by-pass.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","45885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582097","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including the implications for passenger rights. Until we leave, EU law still applies, so EU rules on passenger rights will continue to apply in the UK, alongside national rules.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-20T14:01:26.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582097/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582097/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Passengers: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the protection of passenger rights in the UK.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","45864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582098","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Department does not hold information on the citizenship status of all its staff. Staff are invited to self-declare their nationality on the staff system.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-19T13:06:46.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582098/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582098/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Department for Transport: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many citizens of other EU countries work in (a) his Department and (b) agencies and non-departmental public bodies for which his Department is responsible.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","45902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582099","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>Government is committed to giving disabled people the same access to transport services as other members of society. It also recognises the particularly significant role played by taxis and private hire vehicle (PHV) operators for many disabled people, in helping them to remain active and independent.</p><p> </p><p>It is for local authorities to specify a number of accessible vehicles to be within their licensed taxi and private hire vehicle fleet, and to take account of their public sector equality duties when doing so.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-15T14:32:20.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582099/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582099/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase the number of accessible taxis.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","45915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582100","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Government recognises how important improving access to public transport is for disabled people and is committed to making transport more inclusive.</p><p> </p><p>Since its launch in 2006, the £390m Access for All rail programme (which was further extended with £160m in 2014) has delivered accessible routes at over 150 stations. There are also 68 further projects at various stages of construction or development.</p><p> </p><p>We also recognise that positive interactions with bus drivers can make a big difference to disabled people’s experience of taking the bus. We are working with the bus industry and disabled people to design best practice guidance in delivering disability awareness training which, we hope, will help to give bus drivers the skills and knowledge to assist every disabled passenger.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Bus Services Bill will specifically allow enhanced partnership schemes to require all buses within a local area to provide audible and visual next stop information. Authorities using the new franchising powers will be able to place similar requirements on affected operators. The Government has also agreed to consider amendments on this issue which were tabled during the Bill’s committee stage in the House of Lords.</p><p> </p><p>The Government intends to publish an Accessibility Action Plan for consultation by the end of the year which will present its ambition for further progress on this important agenda.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-15T14:19:43.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582100/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582100/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Public Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve access to public transport for disabled people.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","45938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582101","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>The scheme is currently in the options stage and the next stage is to hold a public consultation on those options. Any developments of local roads would be the responsibility of either the local authority or any developer that is involved in the development of the area.</p><p> </p><p>The current timescales for construction of the scheme are in line with the Governments Roads Investment Strategy 2015 -2020 statement with start of works proposed by March 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-15T12:12:59.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582101/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582101/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582101/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","A14: Kettering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress is being made on designing and planning the new junction 10A on the A14 near Kettering; and when that junction is expected to be built.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","45939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582102","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Civil Aviation Authority issued guidance on 9 September advising air travel passengers to ensure their Samsung Galaxy Note 7 mobile phones remain switched off for the duration of their flight.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance has also been drawn to the attention of aircraft operators.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-20T08:52:02.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582102/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582102/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Aviation: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government has issued guidance to the Aviation Authority on fire risks related to the Samsung Galaxy Note 7.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582103","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Government recognises how important improving access to public transport is for people with visual impairments and is committed to making transport more inclusive.</p><p> </p><p>Buses and coaches subject to the Public Service Vehicles Accessibility Regulations (PSVAR) must incorporate a range of features to make bus travel more accessible for visually impaired people, including priority seating, colour-contrasting hand-holds and step edges, and destination blinds using clear typefaces. PSVAR applies to single-deck buses already, and double-deck buses must comply from 1<sup>st</sup> January 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Bus Services Bill will specifically allow enhanced partnership schemes to require all buses within a local area to provide audible and visual next stop information. Authorities using the new franchising powers will be able to place similar requirements on affected operators. The Government has also agreed to consider amendments on this issue which were tabled during the Bill’s committee stage in the House of Lords.</p><p> </p><p>We are also aware that positive interactions with bus drivers can make a big difference to the experience of visually impaired people taking the bus. We are working with the bus industry and disabled people to design best practice guidance in delivering disability awareness training which, we hope, will help to give bus drivers the skills and knowledge to assist every disabled passenger.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also intends to publish an Accessibility Action Plan for consultation by the end of the year which will present its ambition for further progress on this agenda.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-20T12:20:55.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582103/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582103/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Public Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that public transport is adequately equipped for people with sensory loss.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","45878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582104","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>Clear, accessible information can be very useful to a range of passengers when travelling by bus. Tourists, people new to a given route and those who are disabled may all feel more confident in the knowledge that they will know when to alight when the time comes.</p><p> </p><p>The Bus Services Bill will specifically allow enhanced partnership schemes to require all buses within a local area to provide such information. Authorities using the new franchising powers will be able to place similar requirements on affected operators. The Government has also agreed to consider amendments on this issue which were tabled during the Bill’s committee stage in the House of Lords.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-20T12:25:08.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582104/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582104/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582104/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Bus Services: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase the number of talking buses in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","45879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582105","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>The latest information is published on Network Rail’s website - <a href="http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/" target="_blank">http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/</a> - covering the years 2012-13 to 2014-15.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-15T13:53:20.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582105/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582105/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582105/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-12","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much was paid in compensation for train delays by Network Rail to Govia Thameslink Railway related to Southern railway in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","45883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582106","Wales Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>No citizens of EU countries other than the UK work in the Wales Office, and the department is not responsible for any other agencies or bodies.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-09-15T16:20:08.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582106/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582106/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582106/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-09-12","Wales Office: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many citizens of other EU countries work in (a) his Department and (b) agencies and other bodies for which his Department is responsible.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","45955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582107","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>Anyone can nominate anyone for an honour. The Cabinet Office outreach includes this message in all public communications, including press releases.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-09-16T08:11:56.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582107/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582107/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582107/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-12","Honours: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 44840, on honours: males, if he will take steps to ensure that all future press releases on honours nominations include men when appealing for nominations of people who deserve an honour.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","46010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582108","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Government has no plans to intervene in the National Agreements used in the engineering construction industry. These agreements are voluntary between employer trade associations and trade unions.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-20T13:31:58.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582108/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582108/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582108/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Construction: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of making the National Agreement for the Engineering Construction Industry legally-binding upon employers in the construction industry.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","45956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582109","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>The preliminary statistics for 2015-16 estimate the levels of fraud and error overpayments in Universal Credit at £36 million. These statistics are available in the public domain:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fraud-and-error-in-the-benefit-system-financial-year-201516-preliminary-estimates" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fraud-and-error-in-the-benefit-system-financial-year-201516-preliminary-estimates</a></p><p> </p><p>Final 2015-16 statistics will be published in November 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the nature of the Universal Credit caseload over 2015-16 we do not expect these preliminary statistics to be representative of the eventual Universal Credit steady-state. This was the first time that levels of fraud and error have been measured for Universal Credit as it is a new benefit; we will learn lessons and consider additional strategies as appropriate.</p><p>When Universal Credit is fully rolled out, the government expects to save about £1bn each year through reduced fraud and error and increased ability to monitor changes in income.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>All Universal Credit overpayments are recoverable.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-15T13:59:40.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582109/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582109/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582109/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Universal Credit: Overpayments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much universal credit has been overpaid in each year since roll-out began; and how much of that overpayment has been recoverable.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","45975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582110","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-20","<p>During this period the Department has commissioned a significant number of research reports. Of these, most are either still in progress, or have been completed and published on GOV.UK in line with our standard process. Two publications are currently with the Department awaiting publication. Both comply with the Department’s research publication protocol in accordance with Government Social Research Service guidance. To collate the requested information on all reports commissioned during this period that are yet to be published would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-20T16:49:22.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582110/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582110/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582110/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which reports commissioned by his Department from external bodies between 1 January 2015 and 31 August 2016 have not yet been published; when each report was commissioned for research; what the nature of the research commissioned was; from which external body or individual person the research was commissioned; what the value was of each such piece of research commissioned; on what date each report was received by his Department; for what reasons the research has not yet been published; and when he plans to publish each report.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","45909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582111","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>Investigations of HM Revenue and Customs Tax Credit, Living Together fraud allegations are investigated by Local Service Investigation Team (LSI) and the Central Criminal Intelligence Investigations team (CCIIS) as appropriate within the Fraud and Error Service (FES).</p><p> </p><p>There are currently 1430 employed by the Department. FES investigators are employed to look at all types of welfare fraud from all sources of referral. None are employed specifically to look at individual types of welfare fraud referred from specific sources.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-15T10:37:37.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582111/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582111/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582111/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Welfare Tax Credits: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff are employed by his Department to investigate claims from HM Revenue and Customs that an unreported adult is living in the home of a tax credit claimant; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","45982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582112","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>Pension Credit is an income-related benefit paid out of general taxation which targets help at the poorest pensioners. It is a condition of entitlement for Pension Credit that a person has attained the “qualifying age”, which is linked to the women’s State Pension age. This is the same age at which entitlement to Universal Credit ceases.</p><p> </p><p>Changing the eligibility criteria would mean displacing Universal Credit with Pension Credit. Universal Credit has much better work incentives than Pension Credit, and ensures that work always pays. Universal Credit also disregards pension pots in the means test, encouraging further saving, whereas Pension Credit takes pension pots into account and therefore provides no incentive to increase their size.</p><p> </p><p>For those with disability and care needs, the welfare system already makes provision through benefits and services based on needs assessment. This includes provision for those whose health condition means that it is difficult for them to remain in employment. The Government will be publishing a Green Paper on Work and Health later this year which will consider this issue.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-15T10:47:15.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582112/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582112/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Pension Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to amend the eligibility criteria for pension credit so that all men and women aged 60 and above can access that credit.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","45972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582113","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>The next stages of the delivery of Universal Credit were set out by the Work and Pensions Secretary in a Written Statement to Parliament on 20 July which can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Lords/2016-07-20/HLWS98/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Lords/2016-07-20/HLWS98/</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-15T13:51:35.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582113/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582113/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what date he expects the full roll-out of universal credit to be completed.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","45973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582114","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>Around 9 in 10 (1,990) of the 2,150 SSI and other workers who made an initial claim for benefits have since ended that claim.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-15T13:46:48.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582114/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582114/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Sahaviriya Steel Industries UK: Redcar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people affected by the closure of SSI Redcar have been supported back into employment through the Rapid Response Service.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","45970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582115","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-15","<p>Between 1 September 2015 and 31 August 2016 HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) stopped 57,961 tax credit awards following a decision that the claimant was living with an undeclared partner. Where HMRC identifies an undeclared partner, the single tax credits claim is ended. The customer is able to reclaim in the correct joint capacity if entitlement exists.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-09-15T15:30:02.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582115/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582115/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582115/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-12","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many letters his Department has sent to recipients of tax credits cancelling payments because of claims by HM Revenue and Customs that an unreported adult is living at the claimant's property in the last year; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","45981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582116","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Department’s Rapid Response Service formed part of the SSI Task force set up to provide support to former SSI and supply chain workers.</p><p> </p><p>The Rapid Response Service spend of £2.1M formed part of the overall package of £46m Government funding made available to help people back to work through a range of support measures.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-15T14:44:26.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582116/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582116/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582116/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Sahaviriya Steel Industries UK: Redcar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much funding has been provided to the Rapid Response Service to support those affected by the closure of SSI Redcar in 2015.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","45971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582117","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-19","<p>This information is only available from December 2014, and is routinely published in the Child Maintenance 2012 Scheme – Experimental Statistics<em>. </em>The latest publication includes information up to May 2016, and is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-on-the-2012-statutory-child-maintenance-scheme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-on-the-2012-statutory-child-maintenance-scheme</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-19T14:10:50.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582117/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582117/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582117/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many recipients of child maintenance have received an exemption from the application fee on the grounds of domestic abuse since June 2014.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","45863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582118","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>There are a variety of ways that allegations of Benefit Fraud are collected and received by the DWP including telephone calls to the National Benefit Fraud Hotline, online and Letter and Data matching. Once an allegation has been received and, if it meets the required criteria containing enough information, a Fraud Referral Form is completed which is then entered into the internal Fraud Referral and Information Management System.</p><p> </p><p>The effectiveness of these processes is measured by statistics produced and published in May each year and made available in the public domain. These statistics are used to evaluate, develop and support fraud and error policy, strategy and operational decisions.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-15T15:07:12.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582118/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582118/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Social Security Benefits: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 32920, what processes his Department uses to collect information on allegations of fraudulent benefit claims; and what assessment has been made of the effectiveness of those processes.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","45857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582119","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-20","<p>Tax relief for the cost of care in residential homes would disproportionately benefit those on higher incomes, whilst being of little or no benefit to those on more modest incomes. Furthermore, about half of pensioners do not pay tax and would be excluded from the scope of such a relief.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-09-20T13:58:19.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582119/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582119/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-12","Care Homes: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of making care home expenses tax deductible.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","45892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582120","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the Written Statement made today by the Secretary of State:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-09-15/HCWS154/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-09-15/HCWS154/</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-15T14:09:16.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582120/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582120/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if his Department will exempt crisis, refuge and homeless accommodation from any extension to the Local Housing Allowance cap.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","46067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582121","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the Written Statement made today by the Secretary of State:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-09-15/HCWS154/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2016-09-15/HCWS154/</a></p><p>Full impact and equality impact assessments will be undertaken in due course.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-15T14:12:56.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582121/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582121/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to publish its review into supported accommodation; and whether it has carried out an impact assessment on the extension of the Local Housing Allowance cap.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","46068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582122","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>In 2014/15 the cost of providing free TV licences to those 75 and over in the North East was £26.5m and it is estimated the cost for qualifying residents in Durham County local authority and Easington constituency was £5.3m and £0.8m respectively.</p><p> </p><p>The cost of the free TV licences to those aged 75 and over in the North East for 2015/16 will be published on 21 September on the Gov.uk website. Breakdowns by County and Parliamentary Constituency use that North East expenditure estimate.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-15T11:00:31.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582122/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582122/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to the Exchequer was of providing free television licences to people over 75 years of age in (a) 2014-15 and (b) 2015-16 for qualifying residents in (i) the North East, (ii) Country Durham and (iii) Easington constituency.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","46011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582123","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>Tax Credit fraud referrals are routed from HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to the Fraud and Error Service (FES) within the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) if it is believed there is a DWP benefit interest.</p><p>Investigations of HMRC Tax Credit, Living Together fraud allegations are conducted by Local Service Investigation Team (LSI) within FES. LSI staff are employed to look at all types of welfare fraud from all sources of referral.</p><p>FES investigations are thorough to accurately establish the facts to prove or disprove the allegation made. Investigators use a range of information to confirm the accuracy of Tax Credit, Living Together allegations including local enquiries with bodies like the Police or schools to establish any links between customer and alleged partner. However, lines of enquiry can vary based on the differences in individual cases.</p><p>Please see further the full list of information that can be obtained by FES during investigations in the redacted guidance link below from page 480 onwards.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/523527/fraud-guide-feb-2016.pdf" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/523527/fraud-guide-feb-2016.pdf</strong></a></p><p>On completion of the investigation if evidence is gathered to necessitate an Interview Under Caution the claimant will be notified to attend. Any evidence can be brought voluntarily by the customer to the interview which will then be assessed by DWP. However, following the interview, statements from third parties may be obtained to substantiate the evidence/answers given.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-15T14:31:30.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582123/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582123/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-12","Welfare Tax Credits: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what investigations his Department carries out to confirm the accuracy of information provided by HM Revenue and Customs that an unreported adult is living at the property of a tax credit claimant prior to ceasing to pay the benefit; what evidence his Department accepts from such claimant to show that no unreported adult living at that property; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","46029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582124","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-28","<p>The announcement in July 2013 was an in principle decision to fund, subject to the development of a suitable business case. The reason the funding was not disbursed sooner was because Reaction Engines had not produced a business case that met the Government’s requirements.</p><p>The funding for SABRE was confirmed to Reaction Engines as a grant in December 2015, and milestone payments began in April 2016.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-28T13:32:56.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582124/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582124/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Reaction Engines: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reason the Government's £60 million investment in Reaction Engines to help support the development of SABRE, as announced on 16 July 2013, has been delayed.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","46025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582125","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-26","<p>The Government continues to make compensation payments to all Electricity Intensive Industries, including steel, for the policy costs in their electricity bills. To date we have paid the steel sector over £100 million. We continue to make significant progress in addressing the wider challenges faced by the steel sector, and are working through the Steel Council to ensure the efforts of the sector itself, the Trade Unions, and the Government are all targeted in the right areas.</p><p> </p><p>We are also continuing to work with Tata, the Welsh Government and Trade Unions to support commercial discussions on the future of the company’s remaining UK assets.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-26T10:36:01.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582125/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582125/answer","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582125/answer/previousversion/11811","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether it remains Government policy to (a) offer specific financial support to the UK steel industry and (b) take a 25 per cent equity stake in Tata Steel.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","46062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582126","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-23","<p>As of the end of March 2016 over 3.6 million smart meters were operating under the programme. The Government publishes official statistics on the rollout of smart meters quarterly. The latest release can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-1-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistical-release-and-data-smart-meters-great-britain-quarter-1-2016</a></p><p>The Government receives estimates of forecast smart meter installations from the larger energy suppliers. Their latest projections suggest a further 2.9 million meters are expected to be installed between 1 April 2016 and 31 December 2016.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-23T13:33:45.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582126/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582126/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent estimate he has made of the number of gas and electricity smart meters (a) that have been installed to date and (b) projected to be installed by the end of 2016.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","46074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582127","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-21","<p>Energy Suppliers are required under licence conditions to take all reasonable steps to install smart meters in all of their domestic customers’ premises, and smart or advanced meters in smaller non-domestic sites, by 31 December 2020. There are no plans to amend this obligation.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-21T14:14:45.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582127/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582127/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to review the 2020 deadline for the rollout of smart meters to 100 per cent of UK households after delays to the DCC go-live date.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","46039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582128","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-10","<p>The Government intends to publish an updated cost-benefit analysis for the rollout of smart meters in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-10T14:23:17.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582128/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582128/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to publish an updated cost-benefit analysis of the smart meter rollout programme.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","46038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582129","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-21","<p><em>The Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property)(England and Wales) Regulations 2015</em> requires that all landlords of domestic and non-domestic privately rented property in England and Wales ensure that, from 1 April 2018, their properties reach an energy performance rating of at least an E before granting a tenancy to new or existing tenants, unless a prescribed exemption applies.</p><p>The Department has undertaken, and will continue to undertake, engagement activity with landlord groups to help them understand the requirements of the regulations. Officials are currently preparing guidance to assist non-domestic landlords in complying with their obligations under the regulations, and we will prepare similar guidance for domestic landlords in due course.</p><p>The Department is also developing a landlord exemptions register, a requirement of the Regulations, which will be used by enforcement authorities to help target their enforcement activities, and which will allow landlords to register online any exemptions that apply.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-21T14:15:08.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582129/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582129/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Private Rented Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress his Department has made on ensuring that energy efficiency in the private rented sector is improved to meet new regulations regarding E-grade standards for properties to be let.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","46040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582130","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-28","<p>There is no comprehensive data on the country of registration for the Global Ultimate Owner (GUO) of every company active in the UK pharmaceuticals sector.</p><p>We have incomplete data and therefore cannot accurately calculate how much these companies have invested in the UK in each of the last five years.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-28T13:35:18.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582130/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582130/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Drugs: Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) Japanese, (b) American and (c) European pharmaceutical companies based in the UK; and how much those companies have invested in the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","46041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582131","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-23","<p>The Data and Communications Company is in the final stages of testing the national new data and communications infrastructure for smart metering. It is important to get this right to ensure a good consumer experience from the outset.</p><p>In parallel, the roll out continues to make good progress. Consumers are able to receive smart meters ahead of the national infrastructure going live and more than 3.6 million smart meters are already operating in homes and businesses across the country.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","46036","2016-09-23T13:33:32.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582131/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/582131/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-12","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the revised 30 September 2016 deadline for DCC the go-live on energy consumers.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","46035"
